# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rotary-encoders
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The **reflected binary code** (**RBC**), also known as **reflected binary** (**RB**) or **Gray code** after Frank Gray, is an ordering of the binary numeral system such that two successive values differ in only one bit (binary digit).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] For example, the representation of the decimal value "1" in binary would normally be "001", and "2" would be "010".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In Gray code, these values are represented as "001" and "011".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] That way, incrementing a value from 1 to 2 requires only one bit to change, instead of two.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Gray codes are widely used to prevent spurious output from electromechanical switches and to facilitate error correction in digital communications such as digital terrestrial television and some cable TV systems.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The use of Gray code in these devices helps simplify logic operations and reduce errors in practice.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Many devices indicate position by closing and opening switches.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The problem with natural binary codes is that physical switches are not ideal: it is very unlikely that physical switches will change states exactly in synchrony.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In the transition between the two states shown above, all three switches change state.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In the brief period while all are changing, the switches will read some spurious position.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Even without keybounce, the transition might look like 011 — 001 — 101 — 100.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] When the switches appear to be in position 001, the observer cannot tell if that is the "real" position 1, or a transitional state between two other positions.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] If the output feeds into a sequential system, possibly via combinational logic, then the sequential system may store a false value.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] These codes are also known as *unit-distance*, *single-distance*, *single-step*, *monostrophic* or *syncopic codes*, in reference to the Hamming distance of 1 between adjacent codes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In principle, there can be more than one such code for a given word length, but the term Gray code was first applied to a particular binary code for non-negative integers, the *binary-reflected Gray code*, or **BRGC**.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Stibitz described such a code in a 1941 patent application, granted in 1943.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Frank Gray introduced the term *reflected binary code* in his 1947 patent application, remarking that the code had "as yet no recognized name".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] He derived the name from the fact that it "may be built up from the conventional binary code by a sort of reflection process".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In the standard encoding of the Gray code the least significant bit follows a repetitive pattern of 2 on, 2 off (… 11001100 …); the next digit a pattern of 4 on, 4 off; the *i*-th least significant bit a pattern of 2*i* on 2*i* off.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The most significant digit is an exception to this: for an *n*-bit Gray code, the most significant digit follows the pattern 2*n* − 1 on, 2*n* − 1 off, which is the same (cyclic) sequence of values as for the second-most significant digit, but shifted forwards 2*n* − 2 places.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] For decimal 15 the code rolls over to decimal 0 with only one switch change.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This is called the *cyclic* or *adjacency property* of the code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In modern digital communications, Gray codes play an important role in error correction.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] For example, in a digital modulation scheme such as QAM where data are typically transmitted in symbols of four bits, or more, the signal's constellation diagram is arranged so that the bit patterns conveyed by adjacent constellation points differ by only one bit.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] By combining this with forward error correction capable of correcting single-bit errors, it is possible for a receiver to correct any transmission errors that cause a constellation point to deviate into the area of an adjacent point.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This makes the transmission system less susceptible to noise.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Despite the fact that Stibitz described this code before Gray, the reflected binary code was later named after Gray by others who used it.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Two different 1953 patent applications use "Gray code" as an alternative name for the "reflected binary code"; one of those also lists "minimum error code" and "cyclic permutation code" among the names.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] A 1954 patent application refers to "the Bell Telephone Gray code".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Other names include "cyclic binary code", "cyclic progression code", "cyclic permuting binary" or "cyclic permuted binary" (CPB).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The Gray code is sometimes misattributed to 19th century electrical device inventor Elisha Gray.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Reflected binary codes were applied to mathematical puzzles before they became known to engineers.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The binary-reflected Gray code represents the underlying scheme of the classical Chinese rings puzzle, a sequential mechanical puzzle mechanism described by the French Louis Gros in 1872.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] It can serve as a solution guide for the Towers of Hanoi problem, based on a game by the French Édouard Lucas in 1883.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Similarly, the so-called Towers of Bucharest and Towers of Klagenfurt game configurations yield ternary and pentary Gray codes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Martin Gardner wrote a popular account of the Gray code in his August 1972 "Mathematical Games" column in *Scientific American*.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] When the French engineer Émile Baudot changed from using a 6-unit (6-bit) code to 5-unit code for his printing telegraph system, in 1875 or 1876, he ordered the alphabetic characters on his print wheel using a reflected binary code, and assigned the codes using only three of the bits to vowels.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] With vowels and consonants sorted in their alphabetical order, and other symbols appropriately placed, the 5-bit character code has been recognized as a reflected binary code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This code became known as Baudot code and, with minor changes, was eventually adopted as International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] About the same time, the German-Austrian Otto Schäffler demonstrated another printing telegraph in Vienna using a 5-bit reflected binary code for the same purpose, in 1874.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Frank Gray, who became famous for inventing the signaling method that came to be used for compatible color television, invented a method to convert analog signals to reflected binary code groups using vacuum tube-based apparatus.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Filed in 1947, the method and apparatus were granted a patent in 1953, and the name of Gray stuck to the codes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The "PCM tube" apparatus that Gray patented was made by Raymond W.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Sears of Bell Labs, working with Gray and William M.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Goodall, who credited Gray for the idea of the reflected binary code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Gray was most interested in using the codes to minimize errors in converting analog signals to digital; his codes are still used today for this purpose.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Gray codes are used in linear and rotary position encoders (absolute encoders and quadrature encoders) in preference to weighted binary encoding.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This avoids the possibility that, when multiple bits change in the binary representation of a position, a misread will result from some of the bits changing before others.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] For example, some rotary encoders provide a disk which has an electrically conductive Gray code pattern on concentric rings (tracks).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Each track has a stationary metal spring contact that provides electrical contact to the conductive code pattern.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Together, these contacts produce output signals in the form of a Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Other encoders employ non-contact mechanisms based on optical or magnetic sensors to produce the Gray code output signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Regardless of the mechanism or precision of a moving encoder, position measurement error can occur at specific positions (at code boundaries) because the code may be changing at the exact moment it is read (sampled).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] A binary output code could cause significant position measurement errors because it is impossible to make all bits change at exactly the same time.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] If, at the moment the position is sampled, some bits have changed and others have not, the sampled position will be incorrect.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In the case of absolute encoders, the indicated position may be far away from the actual position and, in the case of incremental encoders, this can corrupt position tracking.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In contrast, the Gray code used by position encoders ensures that the codes for any two consecutive positions will differ by only one bit and, consequently, only one bit can change at a time.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In this case, the maximum position error will be small, indicating a position adjacent to the actual position.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Due to the Hamming distance properties of Gray codes, they are sometimes used in genetic algorithms.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] They may be useful in this field because mutations in the code allow for mostly incremental changes, but occasionally a single bit-change can cause a big leap and lead to new properties.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Gray codes are also used in labelling the axes of Karnaugh maps since 1953 as well as in Händler circle graphs since 1958, both graphical methods for logic circuit minimization.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In modern digital communications, 1D- and 2D-Gray codes play an important role in error prevention before applying an error correction.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] For example, in a digital modulation scheme such as QAM where data is typically transmitted in symbols of 4 bits or more, the signal's constellation diagram is arranged so that the bit patterns conveyed by adjacent constellation points differ by only one bit.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Digital logic designers use Gray codes extensively for passing multi-bit count information between synchronous logic that operates at different clock frequencies.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The logic is considered operating in different "clock domains".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] It is fundamental to the design of large chips that operate with many different clocking frequencies.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] An example would be testing a piping system for all combinations of settings of its manually operated valves.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] A balanced Gray code can be constructed, that flips every bit equally often.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Since bit-flips are evenly distributed, this is optimal in the following way: balanced Gray codes minimize the maximal count of bit-flips for each digit.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Stibitz utilized a reflected binary code in a binary pulse counting device in 1941.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] A typical use of Gray code counters is building a FIFO (first-in, first-out) data buffer that has read and write ports that exist in different clock domains.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The input and output counters inside such a dual-port FIFO are often stored using Gray code to prevent invalid transient states from being captured when the count crosses clock domains.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The updated read and write pointers need to be passed between clock domains when they change, to be able to track FIFO empty and full status in each domain.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Each bit of the pointers is sampled non-deterministically for this clock domain transfer.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] So for each bit, either the old value or the new value is propagated.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Therefore, if more than one bit in the multi-bit pointer is changing at the sampling point, a "wrong" binary value (neither new nor old) can be propagated.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] By guaranteeing only one bit can be changing, Gray codes guarantee that the only possible sampled values are the new or old multi-bit value.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Typically Gray codes of power-of-two length are used.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Sometimes digital buses in electronic systems are used to convey quantities that can only increase or decrease by one at a time, for example the output of an event counter which is being passed between clock domains or to a digital-to-analog converter.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The advantage of Gray codes in these applications is that differences in the propagation delays of the many wires that represent the bits of the code cannot cause the received value to go through states that are out of the Gray code sequence.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This is similar to the advantage of Gray codes in the construction of mechanical encoders, however the source of the Gray code is an electronic counter in this case.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Adding a clocked register after the circuit that converts the count value to Gray code may introduce a clock cycle of latency, so counting directly in Gray code may be advantageous.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] To produce the next count value in a Gray-code counter, it is necessary to have some combinational logic that will increment the current count value that is stored.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] One way to increment a Gray code number is to convert it into ordinary binary code, add one to it with a standard binary adder, and then convert the result back to Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Other methods of counting in Gray code are discussed in a report by Robert W.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Doran, including taking the output from the first latches of the master-slave flip flops in a binary ripple counter.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] In the natural binary code system, the least significant bit indicates if the number is even (0) or odd (1), a property absent in the Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Some processors, like Zilog's Z80, Japan ASCII's R800, and Intel's 8086, have *parity* status flags, which indicate bitwise evenness of some registers, facilitating checking if the number of up bits in them is even.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This can be thought of as built recursively as above from a zero-bit Gray code *G*0 = ( Λ ) consisting of a single entry of zero length.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] These characteristics suggest a simple and fast method of translating a binary value into the corresponding Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Each bit is inverted if the next higher bit of the input value is set to one.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] This can be performed in parallel by a bit-shift and exclusive-or operation if they are available: the *n*th Gray code is obtained by computing $n\oplus \left\lfloor {\tfrac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Prepending a 0 bit leaves the order of the code words unchanged, prepending a 1 bit reverses the order of the code words.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] If the bits at position i of codewords are inverted, the order of neighbouring blocks of $2^{i}$ codewords is reversed.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Thus, performing an exclusive or on a bit $b_{i}$ at position i with the bit $b_{i+1}$ at position $i+1$ leaves the order of codewords intact if $b_{i+1}={\mathtt {0}}$ , and reverses the order of blocks of $2^{i+1}$ codewords if $b_{i+1}={\mathtt {1}}$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Now, this is exactly the same operation as the reflect-and-prefix method to generate the Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] A similar method can be used to perform the reverse translation, but the computation of each bit depends on the computed value of the next higher bit so it cannot be performed in parallel.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Assuming $g_{i}$ is the i th Gray-coded bit ( $g_{0}$ being the most significant bit), and $b_{i}$ is the i th binary-coded bit ( $b_{0}$ being the most-significant bit), the reverse translation can be given recursively: $b_{0}=g_{0}$ , and $b_{i}=g_{i}\oplus b_{i-1}$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] Alternatively, decoding a Gray code into a binary number can be described as a prefix sum of the bits in the Gray code, where each individual summation operation in the prefix sum is performed modulo two.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The bit positions start 0, 1, 0, 2, 0, 1, 0, 3, … See find first set for efficient algorithms to compute these values.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] The following functions in C convert between binary numbers and their associated Gray codes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] While it may seem that Gray-to-binary conversion requires each bit to be handled one at a time, faster algorithms exist.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] On newer processors, the number of ALU instructions in the decoding step can be reduced by taking advantage of the CLMUL instruction set.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p01] If MASK is the constant binary string of ones ended with a single zero digit, then carryless multiplication of MASK with the grey encoding of x will always give either x or its bitwise negation.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] In practice, "Gray code" almost always refers to a binary-reflected Gray code (BRGC).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] However, mathematicians have discovered other kinds of Gray codes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Like BRGCs, each consists of a list of words, where each word differs from the next in only one digit (each word has a Hamming distance of 1 from the next word).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] It is possible to construct binary Gray codes with *n* bits with a length of less than 2*n*, if the length is even.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] One possibility is to start with a balanced Gray code and remove pairs of values at either the beginning and the end, or in the middle.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] OEIS sequence A290772 gives the number of possible Gray sequences of length 2*n* that include zero and use the minimum number of bits.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] There are many specialized types of Gray codes other than the binary-reflected Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] One such type of Gray code is the ***n*-ary Gray code**, also known as a **non-Boolean Gray code**.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] As the name implies, this type of Gray code uses non-Boolean values in its encodings.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] For example, a 3-ary (ternary) Gray code would use the values 0,1,2.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The (*n*, *k*)-*Gray code* is the *n*-ary Gray code with *k* digits.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The (*n*, *k*)-Gray code may be constructed recursively, as the BRGC, or may be constructed iteratively.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] There are other Gray code algorithms for (*n*, *k*)-Gray codes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The (*n*, *k*)-Gray code produced by the above algorithm is always cyclical; some algorithms, such as that by Guan, lack this property when *k* is odd.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] On the other hand, while only one digit at a time changes with this method, it can change by wrapping (looping from *n* − 1 to 0).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] In Guan's algorithm, the count alternately rises and falls, so that the numeric difference between two Gray code digits is always one.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Gray codes are not uniquely defined, because a permutation of the columns of such a code is a Gray code too.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The above procedure produces a code in which the lower the significance of a digit, the more often it changes, making it similar to normal counting methods.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] See also Skew binary number system, a variant ternary number system where at most two digits change on each increment, as each increment can be done with at most one digit carry operation.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Although the binary reflected Gray code is useful in many scenarios, it is not optimal in certain cases because of a lack of "uniformity".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] In **balanced Gray codes**, the number of changes in different coordinate positions are as close as possible.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] A Gray code is *uniform* or *uniformly balanced* if its transition counts are all equal, in which case we have $\lambda _{k}={\tfrac {R^{n}}{n}}$ for all *k*.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Clearly, when $R=2$ , such codes exist only if *n* is a power of 2.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Gray codes can also be *exponentially balanced* if all of their transition counts are adjacent powers of two, and such codes exist for every power of two.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] whereas a balanced 5-bit Gray code has a total of 32 transitions, which cannot be evenly distributed among the positions.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] We will now show a construction and implementation for well-balanced binary Gray codes which allows us to generate an *n*-digit balanced Gray code for every *n*.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The main principle is to inductively construct an (*n* + 2)-digit Gray code $G'$ given an *n*-digit Gray code *G* in such a way that the balanced property is preserved.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Uniform codes can be found when $R\equiv 0{\pmod {4}}$ and $R^{n}\equiv 0{\pmod {n}}$ , and this construction can be extended to the *R*-ary case as well.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Long run (or *maximum gap*) Gray codes maximize the distance between consecutive changes of digits in the same position.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] That is, the minimum run-length of any bit remains unchanged for as long as possible.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Monotonic codes are useful in the theory of interconnection networks, especially for minimizing dilation for linear arrays of processors.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] If we define the *weight* of a binary string to be the number of 1s in the string, then although we clearly cannot have a Gray code with strictly increasing weight, we may want to approximate this by having the code run through two adjacent weights before reaching the next one.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] We can formalize the concept of monotone Gray codes as follows: consider the partition of the hypercube $Q_{n}=(V_{n},E_{n})$ into *levels* of vertices that have equal weight, i.e.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] A monotonic Gray code is then a Hamiltonian path in $Q_{n}$ such that whenever $\delta _{1}\in E_{n}(i)$ comes before $\delta _{2}\in E_{n}(j)$ in the path, then $i\leq j$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] An elegant construction of monotonic *n*-digit Gray codes for any *n* is based on the idea of recursively building subpaths $P_{n,j}$ of length $2\textstyle {\binom {n}{j}}$ having edges in $E_{n}(j)$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Here, $\pi _{n}$ is a suitably defined permutation and $P^{\pi }$ refers to the path *P* with its coordinates permuted by $\pi$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The choice of $\pi _{n}$ which ensures that these codes are indeed Gray codes turns out to be $\pi _{n}=E^{-1}\left(\pi _{n-1}^{2}\right)$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The first few values of $P_{n,j}$ are shown in the table below.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] These monotonic Gray codes can be efficiently implemented in such a way that each subsequent element can be generated in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The algorithm is most easily described using coroutines.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Monotonic codes have an interesting connection to the Lovász conjecture, which states that every connected vertex-transitive graph contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The question has been answered affirmatively for $n\leq 15$ , and the preceding construction for monotonic codes ensures a Hamiltonian path of length at least 0.839‍*N*, where *N* is the number of vertices in the middle-level subgraph.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Another type of Gray code, the **Beckett–Gray code**, is named for Irish playwright Samuel Beckett, who was interested in symmetry.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] His play "Quad" features four actors and is divided into sixteen time periods.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Each period ends with one of the four actors entering or leaving the stage.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The play begins and ends with an empty stage, and Beckett wanted each subset of actors to appear on stage exactly once.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Clearly the set of actors currently on stage can be represented by a 4-bit binary Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Beckett, however, placed an additional restriction on the script: he wished the actors to enter and exit so that the actor who had been on stage the longest would always be the one to exit.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The actors could then be represented by a FIFO queue, so that (of the actors onstage) the actor being dequeued is always the one who was enqueued first.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Beckett was unable to find a Beckett–Gray code for his play, and indeed, an exhaustive listing of all possible sequences reveals that no such code exists for *n* = 4.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] It is known today that such codes do exist for *n* = 2, 5, 6, 7, and 8, and do not exist for *n* = 3 or 4.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] An example of an 8-bit Beckett–Gray code can be found in Donald Knuth's *Art of Computer Programming*.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] According to Sawada and Wong, the search space for *n* = 6 can be explored in 15 hours, and more than 9500 solutions for the case *n* = 7 have been found.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Snake-in-the-box codes, or *snakes*, are the sequences of nodes of induced paths in an *n*-dimensional hypercube graph, and coil-in-the-box codes, or *coils*, are the sequences of nodes of induced cycles in a hypercube.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Viewed as Gray codes, these sequences have the property of being able to detect any single-bit coding error.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Codes of this type were first described by William H.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Kautz in the late 1950s; since then, there has been much research on finding the code with the largest possible number of codewords for a given hypercube dimension.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Yet another kind of Gray code is the **single-track Gray code** (STGC) developed by Norman B.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Spedding and refined by Hiltgen, Paterson and Brandestini in *Single-track Gray Codes* (1996).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The STGC is a cyclical list of *P* unique binary encodings of length n such that two consecutive words differ in exactly one position, and when the list is examined as a *P* × *n* matrix, each column is a cyclic shift of the first column.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The name comes from their use with rotary encoders, where a number of tracks are being sensed by contacts, resulting for each in an output of 0 or 1.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] To reduce noise due to different contacts not switching at exactly the same moment in time, one preferably sets up the tracks so that the data output by the contacts are in Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] To get high angular accuracy, one needs lots of contacts; in order to achieve at least 1° accuracy, one needs at least 360 distinct positions per revolution, which requires a minimum of 9 bits of data, and thus the same number of contacts.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] If all contacts are placed at the same angular position, then 9 tracks are needed to get a standard BRGC with at least 1° accuracy.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] However, if the manufacturer moves a contact to a different angular position (but at the same distance from the center shaft), then the corresponding "ring pattern" needs to be rotated the same angle to give the same output.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] If the most significant bit (the inner ring in Figure 1) is rotated enough, it exactly matches the next ring out.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Since both rings are then identical, the inner ring can be cut out, and the sensor for that ring moved to the remaining, identical ring (but offset at that angle from the other sensor on that ring).
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Those two sensors on a single ring make a quadrature encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] That reduces the number of tracks for a "1° resolution" angular encoder to 8 tracks.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Reducing the number of tracks still further cannot be done with BRGC.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] For many years, Torsten Sillke and other mathematicians believed that it was impossible to encode position on a single track such that consecutive positions differed at only a single sensor, except for the 2-sensor, 1-track quadrature encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] So for applications where 8 tracks were too bulky, people used single-track incremental encoders (quadrature encoders) or 2-track "quadrature encoder + reference notch" encoders.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Spedding, however, registered a patent in 1994 with several examples showing that it was possible.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Although it is not possible to distinguish 2*n* positions with *n* sensors on a single track, it *is* possible to distinguish close to that many.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Etzion and Paterson conjecture that when *n* is itself a power of 2, *n* sensors can distinguish at most 2*n* − 2*n* positions and that for prime *n* the limit is 2*n* − 2 positions.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The authors went on to generate a 504-position single track code of length 9 which they believe is optimal.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Since this number is larger than 28 = 256, more than 8 sensors are required by any code, although a BRGC could distinguish 512 positions with 9 sensors.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Each column is a cyclic shift of the first column, and from any row to the next row only one bit changes.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The single-track nature (like a code chain) is useful in the fabrication of these wheels (compared to BRGC), as only one track is needed, thus reducing their cost and size.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The Gray code nature is useful (compared to chain codes, also called De Bruijn sequences), as only one sensor will change at any one time, so the uncertainty during a transition between two discrete states will only be plus or minus one unit of angular measurement the device is capable of resolving.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Since this 30 degree example was added, there has been a lot of interest in examples with higher angular resolution.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] In 2008, Gary Williams, based on previous work, discovered a 9-bit single track Gray code that gives a 1 degree resolution.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] This Gray code was used to design an actual device which was published on the site Thingiverse.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] This device was designed by etzenseep (Florian Bauer) in September 2022.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Two-dimensional Gray codes are used in communication to minimize the number of bit errors in quadrature amplitude modulation (QAM) adjacent points in the constellation.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] In a typical encoding the horizontal and vertical adjacent constellation points differ by a single bit, and diagonal adjacent points differ by 2 bits.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] If a subsection of a specific codevalue is extracted from that value, for example the last 3 bits of a 4-bit Gray code, the resulting code will be an "excess Gray code".
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] This code shows the property of counting backwards in those extracted bits if the original value is further increased.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Reason for this is that Gray-encoded values do not show the behaviour of overflow, known from classic binary encoding, when increasing past the "highest" value.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Example: The highest 3-bit Gray code, 7, is encoded as (0)100.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Adding 1 results in number 8, encoded in Gray as 1100.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The last 3 bits do not overflow and count backwards if you further increase the original 4 bit code.
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] The mapping is suitably extended to an isometry of the Hamming spaces $\mathbb {Z} _{2}^{2m}$ and $\mathbb {Z} _{4}^{m}$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/gray-code-p02] Its importance lies in establishing a correspondence between various "good" but not necessarily linear codes as Gray-map images in $\mathbb {Z} _{2}^{2}$ of ring-linear codes from $\mathbb {Z} _{4}$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] An **incremental encoder** is a linear or rotary electromechanical device that has two output signals, *A* and *B*, which issue pulses when the device is moved.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Together, the *A* and *B* signals indicate both the occurrence of and direction of movement.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Many incremental encoders have an additional output signal, typically designated *index* or *Z*, which indicates the encoder is located at a particular reference position.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Also, some encoders provide a status output (typically designated *alarm*) that indicates internal fault conditions such as a bearing failure or sensor malfunction.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Unlike an absolute encoder, an incremental encoder does not indicate absolute position; it only reports changes in position and the corresponding direction of movement for each change.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, to determine absolute position at any particular moment, it is necessary to send the encoder signals to an *incremental encoder interface*, which in turn will "track" and report the encoder's absolute position.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoders report position increments nearly instantaneously, which allows them to monitor the movements of high speed mechanisms in near real-time.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Because of this, incremental encoders are commonly used in applications that require precise measurement and control of position and velocity.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] An incremental encoder generates its *A* and *B* output signals using a quadrature encoding technique.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When the encoder moves at a constant velocity, the *A* and *B* signals are square waves with a 90° phase difference between them, allowing detection of both movement and direction.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] At any particular time, the phase difference between the *A* and *B* signals will be positive or negative depending on the encoder's direction of movement.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In the case of a rotary encoder, the phase difference is +90° for clockwise rotation and −90° for counter-clockwise rotation, or vice versa, depending on the device design.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The frequency of the pulses on the *A* or *B* output is directly proportional to the encoder's velocity (rate of position change); higher frequencies indicate rapid movement, whereas lower frequencies indicate slower speeds.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Static, unchanging signals are output on *A* and *B* when the encoder is motionless.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In the case of a rotary encoder, the frequency indicates the speed of the encoder's shaft rotation, and in linear encoders the frequency indicates the speed of linear traversal.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Quadrature encoder outputs can be produced by a quadrature-offset pattern read by aligned sensors (left diagram), or by a simple pattern read by offset sensors (right diagram).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The resolution of an incremental encoder is a measure of the precision of the position information it produces.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Encoder resolution is typically specified in terms of the number of *A* (or *B*) pulses per unit displacement or, equivalently, the number of *A* (or *B*) square wave cycles per unit displacement.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In the case of rotary encoders, resolution is specified as the number of pulses per revolution (PPR) or cycles per revolution (CPR), whereas linear encoder resolution is typically specified as the number of pulses issued for a particular linear traversal distance (e.g., 1000 pulses per mm).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This differs from the measurement resolution, which refers to the smallest change in position that the encoder can detect.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Each signal edge on output *A* or *B* corresponds to a discrete position change.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Because one full square-wave cycle on *A* (or *B*) includes four edges—rising *A*, rising *B*, falling *A*, and falling *B*—the measurement resolution is one-fourth of the distance represented by a full cycle.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] For example, a linear encoder with a resolution of 1000 pulses per millimeter has a per-cycle resolution of 1 μm (1 mm / 1000 cycles), yielding a measurement resolution of 250 nm (1 μm / 4).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When moving at constant velocity, an ideal incremental encoder would output perfect square waves on *A* and *B* (i.e., the pulses would be exactly 180° wide and the duty cycle would be 50%) with a phase difference of exactly 90° between *A* and *B* signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In real encoders, however, due to sensor imperfections and speed variations, the pulse widths are never exactly 180° and the phase difference is never exactly 90°.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Furthermore, the *A* and *B* pulse widths vary from one cycle to another (and from each other) and the phase difference varies at every *A* and *B* signal edge.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, both the pulse width and phase difference will vary over a range of values.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] For any particular encoder, the pulse width and phase difference ranges are defined by "symmetry" and "phase" (or "phasing") specifications, respectively.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] For example, in the case of an encoder with symmetry specified as 180° ±25°, the width of every output pulse is guaranteed to be at least 155° and no more than 205°.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Similarly, with phase specified as 90° ±20°, the phase difference at every *A* or *B* edge will be at least 70° and no more than 110°.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoders employ various types of electronic circuits to drive (transmit) their output signals, and manufacturers often have the ability to build a particular encoder model with any of several driver types.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Commonly available driver types include open collector, mechanical, push-pull and differential RS-422.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Open collector drivers (using an NPN transistor or open drain drivers using an n-type MOSFET) allow operation over a wide range of signal voltages and often can sink significant output current, making them useful for directly driving current loops, opto-isolators and fiber optic transmitters.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Because it cannot source current, the output of an open-collector driver must be connected to a positive DC voltage through a pull-up resistor.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Some encoders provide an internal resistor for this purpose; others do not and thus require an external pull-up resistor.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In the latter case, the resistor typically is located near the encoder interface to improve noise immunity.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The encoder's high-level logic signal voltage is determined by the voltage applied to the pull-up resistor (*VOH* in the schematic), whereas the low-level output current is determined by both the signal voltage and load resistance (including pull-up resistor).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When the driver switches from the low to the high logic level, the load resistance and circuit capacitance act together to form a low-pass filter, which stretches (increases) the signal's rise time and thus limits its maximum switching frequency.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Mechanical (or *contact*) incremental encoders use sliding electrical contacts to directly generate the *A* and *B* output signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Typically, the contacts are electrically connected to signal ground when closed so that the outputs will be "driven" low, effectively making them mechanical equivalents of open collector drivers and therefore subject to the same signal conditioning requirements (i.e. external pull-up resistor).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The maximum output frequency is limited by the same factors that affect open-collector outputs, and further limited by contact bounce (which must be filtered) and by the operating speed of the mechanical contacts, thus making these devices impractical for high frequency operation.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Furthermore, the contacts experience mechanical wear under normal operation, which limits the life of these devices.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] On the other hand, mechanical encoders may be relatively inexpensive and have no internal, active electronics.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] These attributes make mechanical encoders a good fit for hand-operated controls (e.g. volume controls in audio equipment and voltage controls in bench power supplies) and a variety of other low duty, low frequency applications.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Push-pull outputs (e.g., TTL) typically are used for direct interface to logic circuitry.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Examples of this include CMMs and CNC machinery, industrial robotics, factory automation, and motion platforms used in aircraft and spacecraft simulators.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When RS-422 outputs are employed, the encoder provides a differential conductor pair for every logic output; for example, "A" and "/A" are commonly used designations for the active-high and active-low differential pair comprising the encoder's *A* logic output.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, the encoder interface must provide RS-422 line receivers to convert the incoming RS-422 pairs to single-ended logic.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoders are commonly used to monitor the physical positions of mechanical devices.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The incremental encoder is mechanically attached to the device to be monitored so that its output signals will change as the device moves.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Example devices include the balls in mechanical computer mice and trackballs, control knobs in electronic equipment, and rotating shafts in radar antennas.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] An incremental encoder does not keep track of, nor do its outputs indicate the current encoder position; it only reports incremental changes in position.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, to determine the encoder's position at any particular moment, it is necessary to provide external electronics which will "track" the position.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This external circuitry, which is known as an incremental encoder interface, tracks position by counting incremental position changes.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] As it receives each report of incremental position change (indicated by a transition of the *A* or *B* signal), an encoder interface will take into account the phase relationship between *A* and *B* and, depending on the sign of the phase difference, count up or down.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The cumulative "counts" value indicates the distance traveled since tracking began.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This mechanism ensures accurate position tracking in bidirectional applications and, in unidirectional applications, prevents false counts that would otherwise result from vibration or mechanical dithering near an AB code transition.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Often the encoder counts must be expressed in units such as meters, miles or revolutions.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Typically this calculation is performed by a computer which reads the counts from the incremental encoder interface.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In order for an incremental encoder interface to track and report absolute position, the encoder counts must be correlated to a reference position in the mechanical system to which the encoder is attached.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This is commonly done by *homing* the system, which consists of moving the mechanical system (and encoder) until it aligns with a reference position, and then jamming the associated absolute position counts into the encoder interface's counter.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] A proximity sensor is built into some mechanical systems to facilitate homing, which outputs a signal when the mechanical system is in its "home" (reference) position.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In such cases, the mechanical system is homed by moving it until the encoder interface receives the sensor signal, whereupon the corresponding position value is jammed into the position counter.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In some rotating mechanical systems (e.g. rotating radar antennas), the "position" of interest is the rotational angle relative to a reference orientation.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] These typically employ a rotary incremental encoder that has an *index* (or *Z*) output signal.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The *index* signal is asserted when the shaft is in its reference orientation, which causes the encoder interface to jam the reference angle into its position counter.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Some incremental encoder applications lack reference position detectors and therefore must implement homing by other means.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] For example a computer, when using a mouse or trackball pointing device, typically will home the device by assuming a central, initial screen position upon booting, and jam the corresponding counts into the X and Y position counters.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoders are commonly used to measure the speed of mechanical systems.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This may be done for monitoring purposes or to provide feedback for motion control, or both.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Widespread applications of this include speed control of radar antenna rotation and material conveyors, and motion control in robotics, CMM and CNC machines.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoder interfaces are primarily concerned with tracking mechanical displacement and usually do not directly measure speed.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, speed must be indirectly measured by taking the derivative of the position with respect to time.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The position signal is inherently quantized, which poses challenges for taking the derivative due to quantization error, especially at low speeds.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Encoder speed can be determined either by counting or by timing the encoder output pulses (or edges).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The resulting value indicates a frequency or period, respectively, from which speed can be calculated.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The speed is proportional to frequency, and inversely proportional to period.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] If the position signal is sampled (a discrete time signal), the pulses (or pulse edges) are detected and counted by the interface, and speed is typically calculated by a computer which has read access to the interface.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] To do this, the computer reads the position counts $C_{0}$ from the interface at time $T_{0}$ and then, at some later time $T_{1}$ reads the counts again to obtain $C_{1}$ .
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The resulting speed value is expressed as counts per unit time (e.g., counts per second).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In practice, however, it is often necessary to express the speed in standardized units such as meters per second, revolutions per minute (RPM), or miles per hour (MPH).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In such cases, the software will take into account the relationship between counts and desired distance units, as well as the ratio of the sampling period to desired time units.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When measuring speed this way, the measurement resolution is proportional to both the encoder resolution and the sampling period (the elapsed time between the two samples); measurement resolution will become higher as the sampling period increases.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Alternatively, a speed measurement can be reported at each encoder output pulse by measuring the pulse width or period.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When this method is used, measurements are triggered at specific positions instead of at specific times.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The speed calculation is the same as shown above (counts / time), although in this case the measurement start and stop times ( $T_{0}$ and $T_{1}$ ) are provided by a time reference.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This technique avoids position quantization error but introduces errors related to quantization of the time reference.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Also, it is more sensitive to sensor non-idealities such as phase errors, symmetry errors, and variations in the transition locations from their nominal values.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] An **incremental encoder interface** is an electronic circuit that receives signals from an incremental encoder, processes the signals to produce absolute position and other information, and makes the resulting information available to external circuitry.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoder interfaces are implemented in a variety of ways, including as ASICs, as IP blocks within FPGAs, as dedicated peripheral interfaces in microcontrollers, or as software (via interrupts or polling GPIOs).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Regardless of the implementation, the interface must sample the encoder's *A* and *B* output signals frequently enough to detect every AB state change before the next state change occurs.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Upon detecting a state change, it will increment or decrement the position counts based on whether *A* leads or trails *B*.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This is typically done by storing a copy of the previous AB state and, upon state change, using the current and previous AB states to determine movement direction.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoder interfaces use various types of electronic circuits to receive encoder-generated signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] These line receivers serve as buffers to protect downstream interface circuitry and, in many cases, also provide signal conditioning functions.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoder interfaces typically employ Schmitt trigger inputs to receive signals from encoders that have single-ended (e.g., push-pull, open collector) outputs.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This type of line receiver inherently rejects low-level noise (by means of its input hysteresis) and protects downstream circuitry from invalid (and possibly destructive) logic signal levels.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] RS-422 line receivers are commonly used to receive signals from encoders that have differential outputs.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This type of receiver rejects common-mode noise and converts the incoming differential signals to the single-ended form required by downstream logic circuits.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In mission-critical systems, an encoder interface may be required to detect loss of input signals due to encoder power loss, signal driver failure, cable fault or cable disconnect.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This is usually accomplished by using enhanced RS-422 line receivers which detect the absence of valid input signals and report this condition via a "signal lost" status output.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In normal operation, glitches (brief pulses) may appear on the status outputs during input state transitions; typically, the encoder interface will filter the status signals to prevent these glitches from being erroneously interpreted as lost signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Depending on the interface, subsequent processing may include generating an interrupt request upon detecting signal loss, and sending notification to the application for error logging or failure analysis.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] An incremental encoder interface largely consists of sequential logic which is paced by a clock signal.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] However, the incoming encoder signals are asynchronous with respect to the interface clock because their timing is determined solely by encoder movement.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, the output signals from the *A* and *B* (also *Z* and *alarm*, if used) line receivers must be synchronized to the interface clock, both to avoid errors due to metastability and to coerce the signals into the clock domain of the quadrature decoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Typically this synchronization is performed by independent, single-signal synchronizers such as the two flip-flop synchronizer seen here.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] At very high clock frequencies, or when a very low error rate is needed, the synchronizers may include additional flip-flops in order to achieve an acceptably low bit error rate.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In many cases an encoder interface must filter the synchronized encoder signals before further processing them.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This may be required in order to reject low-level noise and brief, large-amplitude noise spikes commonly found in motor applications and, in the case of mechanical-type encoders, to debounce *A* and *B* to avoid count errors due to mechanical contact bounce.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Hardware-based interfaces often provide programmable filters for the encoder signals, which provide a wide range of filter settings and thus allow them to debounce contacts or suppress transients resulting from noise or slowly slewing signals, as needed.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In software-based interfaces, *A* and *B* typically are connected to GPIOs that are sampled (via polling or edge interrupts) and debounced by software.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Incremental encoder interfaces commonly use a **quadrature decoder** to convert the *A* and *B* signals into the *direction* and *count enable* (clock enable) signals needed for controlling a bidirectional (up- and down-counting) synchronous counter.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Typically, a quadrature decoder is implemented as a finite-state machine (FSM) which simultaneously samples the *A* and *B* signals and thus produces amalgamate "AB" samples.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] As each new AB sample is acquired, the FSM will store the previous AB sample for later analysis.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The FSM evaluates the differences between the new and previous AB states and generates *direction* and *count enable* signals as appropriate for the detected AB state sequence.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In any two consecutive AB samples, the logic level of *A* or *B* may change or both levels may remain unchanged, but in normal operation *A* and *B* will never both change.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In this regard, each AB sample is effectively a two-bit Gray code.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When only *A* or *B* changes state, it is assumed that the encoder has moved one increment of its measurement resolution and, accordingly, the quadrature decoder will assert its *count enable* output to allow the counts to change.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Depending on the encoder's direction of travel (forward or reverse), the decoder will assert or negate its *direction* output to cause the counts to increment or decrement (or vice versa).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When neither *A* nor *B* changes, it is assumed that the encoder has not moved and so the quadrature decoder negates its *count enable* output, thereby causing the counts to remain unchanged.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] If both the *A* and *B* logic states change in consecutive AB samples, the quadrature decoder has no way of determining how many increments, or in what direction the encoder has moved.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This can happen if the encoder speed is too fast for the decoder to process (i.e., the rate of AB state changes exceeds the quadrature decoder's sampling rate; see Nyquist rate) or if the *A* or *B* signal is noisy.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In many encoder applications this is a catastrophic event because the counter no longer provides an accurate indication of encoder position.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, quadrature decoders often will output an additional *error* signal which is asserted when the *A* and *B* states change simultaneously.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Due to the severity and time-sensitive nature of this condition, the *error* signal is often connected to an interrupt request.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] A quadrature decoder does not necessarily allow the counts to change for every incremental position change.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When a decoder detects an incremental position change (due to a transition of *A* or *B*, but not both), it may allow the counts to change or it may inhibit counting, depending on the AB state transition and the decoder's *clock multiplier*.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The clock multiplier of a quadrature decoder is so named because it results in a count rate which is a multiple of the *A* or *B* pulse frequency.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Depending on the decoder's design, the clock multiplier may be hardwired into the design or it may be run-time configurable via input signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] The clock multiplier value may be one, two or four (typically designated "x1", "x2" and "x4", or "1x", "2x" and "4x").
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In the case of a x4 multiplier, the counts will change for every AB state change, thereby resulting in a count rate equal to four times the *A* or *B* frequency.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] From an application's perspective, the fundamental purpose of an incremental encoder interface is to report position information on demand.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Depending on the application, this may be as simple as allowing the computer to read the position counter at any time under program control.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In more complex systems, the position counter may be sampled and processed by intermediate state machines, which in turn make the samples available to the computer.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] An encoder interface typically employs a sample register to facilitate position reporting.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In the simple case where the computer demands position information under program control, the interface will sample the position counter (i.e., copy the current position counts to the sample register) and then the computer will read the counts from the sample register.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This mechanism results in atomic operation and thus ensures the integrity of the sample data, which might otherwise be at risk (e.g., if the sample's word size exceeds the computer's word size).
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In some cases the computer may not be able to programmatically (via programmed I/O) acquire position information with adequate timing precision.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] For example, the computer may be unable to demand samples on a timely periodic schedule (e.g., for speed measurement) due to software timing variability.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Also, in some applications it is necessary to demand samples upon the occurrence of external events, and the computer may be unable to do so in a timely manner.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] At higher encoder speeds and resolutions, position measurement errors can occur even when interrupts are used to demand samples, because the encoder may move between the time the IRQ is signaled and the sample demand is issued by the interrupt handler.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] To overcome this limitation, it is common for an incremental encoder interface to implement hardware-triggered sampling, which enables it to sample the position counter at precisely controlled times as dictated by a trigger input signal.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This is important when the position must be sampled at particular times or in response to physical events, and essential in applications such as multi-axis motion control and CMM, in which the position counters of multiple encoder interfaces (one per axis) must be simultaneously sampled.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] In many applications the computer must know precisely when each sample was acquired and, if the interface has multiple trigger inputs, which signal triggered the sample acquisition.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] To satisfy these requirements, the interface typically will include a timestamp and trigger information in every sample.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Sampling triggers are often asynchronous with respect to software execution.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consequently, when the position counter is sampled in response to a trigger signal, the computer must be notified (typically via interrupt) that a sample is available.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] This allows the software to be event-driven (vs. polled), which facilitates responsive system behavior and eliminates polling overhead.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] Consecutive sampling triggers may occur faster than the computer can process the resulting samples.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When this happens, the information in the sample register will be overwritten before it can be read by the computer, resulting in data loss.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] To avoid this problem, some incremental encoder interfaces provide a FIFO buffer for samples.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] As each sample is acquired, it is stored in the FIFO.
[src:rotary-encoders/incremental-encoder] When the computer demands a sample, it is allowed to read the oldest sample in the FIFO.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] A **linear encoder** is a sensor, transducer or readhead paired with a **scale** that encodes position.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The sensor reads the scale in order to convert the encoded position into an analog or digital signal, which can then be decoded into position by a digital readout (DRO) or motion controller.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The encoder can be either *incremental* or *absolute.* In an incremental system, position is determined by motion over time; in contrast, in an absolute system, motion is determined by position over time.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Linear encoder technologies include optical, magnetic, inductive, capacitive and eddy current.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Optical technologies include shadow, self imaging and interferometric.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Linear encoders are used in metrology instruments, motion systems, inkjet printers and high precision machining tools ranging from digital calipers and coordinate measuring machines to stages, CNC mills, manufacturing gantry tables and semiconductor steppers.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Optical linear encoders dominate the high resolution market and may employ shuttering/moiré, diffraction or holographic principles.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Optical encoders are the most accurate of the standard styles of encoders, and the most commonly used in industrial automation applications.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] When specifying an optical encoder, it's important that the encoder have extra protection built in to prevent contamination from dust, vibration and other conditions common to industrial environments.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Typical incremental scale periods vary from hundreds of micrometers down to sub-micrometer.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Interpolation can provide resolutions as fine as a nanometer.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Light sources used include infrared LEDs, visible LEDs, miniature light-bulbs and laser diodes.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Magnetic linear encoders employ either active (magnetized) or passive (variable reluctance) scales and position may be sensed using sense-coils, Hall effect or magnetoresistive readheads.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] With coarser scale periods than optical encoders (typically a few hundred micrometers to several millimeters) resolutions in the order of a micrometer are the norm.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Capacitive linear encoders work by sensing the capacitance between a reader and scale.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Typical applications are digital calipers.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] One of the disadvantages is the sensitivity to uneven dirt, which can locally change the relative permittivity.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Inductive technology is robust to contaminants, allowing calipers and other measurement tools that are coolant-proof.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] A well-known application of the inductive measuring principle is the Inductosyn.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Maxon makes an example (rotary encoder) product (the MILE encoder).
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The sensors are based on an image correlation method.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The sensor takes subsequent pictures from the surface being measured and compares the images for displacement.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Resolutions down to a nanometer are possible.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Measurement application include coordinate-measuring machines (CMM), laser scanners, calipers, gear measurement, tension testers, and digital read outs (DROs).
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Servo controlled motion systems employ linear encoder so as to provide accurate, high-speed movement.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Typical applications include robotics, machine tools, pick-and-place PCB assembly equipment; semiconductors handling and test equipment, wire bonders, printers and digital presses.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Linear encoders can have analog or digital outputs.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The industry standard analog output for linear encoders is sine and cosine quadrature signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] These are usually transmitted differentially so as to improve noise immunity.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] An early industry standard was 12 μA peak-peak current signals but more recently this has been replaced with 1V peak to peak voltage signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Compared to digital transmission, the analog signals' lower bandwidth helps to minimise EMC emissions.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Quadrature sine/cosine signals can be monitored easily by using an oscilloscope in XY mode to display a circular Lissajous figure.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Highest accuracy signals are obtained if the Lissajous figure is circular (no gain or phase error) and perfectly centred.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Modern encoder systems employ circuitry to trim these error mechanisms automatically.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The overall accuracy of the linear encoder is a combination of the scale accuracy and errors introduced by the readhead.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Scale contributions to the error budget include linearity and slope (scaling factor error).
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Readhead error mechanisms are usually described as *cyclic error* or *sub-divisional error (SDE)* as they repeat every scale period.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The largest contributor to readhead inaccuracy is signal offset, followed by signal imbalance (ellipticity) and phase error (the quadrature signals not being exactly 90° apart).
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Overall signal size does not affect encoder accuracy, however, signal-to-noise and jitter performance may degrade with smaller signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Automatic signal compensation mechanisms can include *automatic offset compensation (AOC), automatic balance compensation (ABC) and automatic gain control (AGC)*.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Phase is more difficult to compensate dynamically and is usually applied as one time compensation during installation or calibration.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Other forms of inaccuracy include signal distortion (frequently harmonic distortion of the sine/cosine signals).
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] A linear incremental encoder has two digital output signals, A and B, which issue quadrature squarewaves.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Depending on its internal mechanism, an encoder may derive A and B directly from sensors which are fundamentally digital in nature, or it may interpolate its internal, analogue sine/cosine signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] In the latter case, the interpolation process effectively sub-divides the scale period and thereby achieves higher measurement resolution.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] In either case, the encoder will output quadrature squarewaves, with the distance between edges of the two channels being the resolution of the encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The reference mark or index pulse is also output in digital form, as a pulse which is one to four units-of-resolution wide.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The output signals may be directly transmitted to a digital incremental encoder interface for position tracking.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The major advantages of linear incremental encoders are improved noise immunity, high measurement accuracy, and low-latency reporting of position changes.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] However, the high frequency, fast signal edges may produce more EMC emissions.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] As well as analog or digital incremental output signals, linear encoders can provide *absolute* reference or positioning signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Most incremental, linear encoders can produce an index or reference mark pulse providing a datum position along the scale for use at power-up or following a loss of power.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] This index signal must be able to identify position within one, unique period of the scale.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The reference mark may comprise a single feature on the scale, an autocorrelator pattern (typically a Barker code) or a chirp pattern.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Distance coded reference marks (DCRM) are placed onto the scale in a unique pattern allowing a minimal movement (typically moving past two reference marks) to define the readhead's position.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Multiple, equally spaced reference marks may also be placed onto the scale such that following installation, the desired marker can either be selected - usually via a magnet or optically or unwanted ones deselected using labels or by being painted over.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] With suitably encoded scales (multitrack, vernier, digital code, or pseudo-random code) an encoder can determine its position without movement or needing to find a reference position.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Such absolute encoders also communicate using serial communication protocols.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Many of these protocols are proprietary (e.g., Fanuc, Mitsubishi, FeeDat (Fagor Automation), Heidenhain EnDat, DriveCliq, Panasonic, Yaskawa) but open standards such as BiSS are now appearing, which avoid tying users to a particular supplier.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Many linear encoders include built-in limit switches; either optical or magnetic.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Two limit switches are frequently included such that on power-up the controller can determine if the encoder is at an end-of-travel and in which direction to drive the axis.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Linear encoders may be either *enclosed* or *open*.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Enclosed linear encoders are employed in dirty, hostile environments such as machine-tools.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] They typically comprise an aluminium extrusion enclosing a glass or metal scale.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Flexible lip seals allow an internal, guided readhead to read the scale.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Accuracy is limited due to the friction and hysteresis imposed by this mechanical arrangement.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] For the highest accuracy, lowest measurement hysteresis and lowest friction applications, open linear encoders are used.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Linear encoders may use transmissive (glass) or reflective scales, employing Ronchi or phase gratings.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Scale materials include chrome on glass, metal (stainless steel, gold plated steel, Invar), ceramics (Zerodur) and plastics.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] The scale may be self-supporting, thermally mastered to the substrate (via adhesive or adhesive tape) or *track* mounted.
[src:rotary-encoders/linear-encoder] Track mounting may allow the scale to maintain its own coefficient of thermal expansion and allows large equipment to be broken down for shipment.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] A **resolver** is a type of rotary electrical transformer used for measuring degrees of rotation.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] It is considered an analog device, and has digital counterparts such as the digital resolver, rotary (or pulse) encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] A rotating coil induces voltage in two stationary coils, and by comparing the phase of the signal in the two secondaries, the angle can be accurately determined.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] These systems were commonly used in mechanical control systems, for instance, counting the number of revolutions of a screw jack to move an aircraft's flaps to a specific extension.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The most common type of resolver is the brushless transmitter resolver (other types are described at the end).
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] On the outside, this type of resolver may look like a small electrical motor having a stator and rotor.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] On the inside, the configuration of the wire windings makes it different.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The stator portion of the resolver houses three windings: an exciter winding and two two-phase windings, usually labeled "x" and "y".
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The exciter winding is located on the top and is mounted such that it can rotate around the horizontal axis to produce a rotary transformer.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The two two-phase windings are on the bottom, wound on a lamination and mounted at 90 degrees from each other.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The rotor houses a coil, which is the secondary winding of the rotating transformer, and a separate primary winding in a lamination, exciting the two two-phase windings on the stator.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The primary winding of the transformer, fixed to the stator, is excited by a sinusoidal electric current, which by electromagnetic induction induces current in the rotor.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] As these windings are arranged on the axis of the resolver, the same current is induced no matter what its position.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] This current then flows through the other winding on the rotor, in turn inducing current in its secondary windings, the two-phase windings back on the stator.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The two two-phase windings produce a sine and cosine feedback current.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The relative magnitudes of the two-phase voltages are measured and used to determine the angle of the rotor relative to the stator.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Upon one full revolution, the feedback signals repeat their waveforms.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] This device may also appear in non-brushless type, i.e., only consisting in two lamination stacks, rotor and stator.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Resolvers can perform very accurate analog conversion from polar to rectangular coordinates.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Shaft angle is the polar angle, and excitation voltage is the magnitude.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The outputs are the [x] and [y] components.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Resolvers with four-lead rotors can rotate [x] and [y] coordinates, with the shaft position giving the desired rotation angle.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Resolvers with four output leads are general sine/cosine computational devices.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] For the position evaluation, resolver-to-digital converters are commonly used.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] They convert the sine and cosine signal to a binary signal (10 to 16 bits wide) that can more easily be used by the controller.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Basic resolvers are two-pole resolvers, meaning that the angular information is the mechanical angle of the stator.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] These devices can deliver the absolute angle position.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Other types of resolver are multipole resolvers.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] They have 2*p* poles (*p* pole pairs), and thus can deliver *p* cycles in one rotation of the rotor: the electrical angle is *p* times the mechanical angle.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Some types of resolvers include both types, with the 2-pole windings used for absolute position and the multipole windings for accurate position.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Two-pole resolvers can usually reach angular accuracy up to about ±5′, whereas a multipole resolver can provide better accuracy, up to 10″ for 16-pole resolvers, to even 1″ for 128-pole resolvers.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Multipole resolvers may also be used for monitoring multipole electrical motors.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] This device can be used in any application in which the exact rotation of an object relative to another object is needed, such as in a rotary antenna platform or a robot.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] In practice, the resolver is usually directly mounted to an electric motor.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The resolver feedback signals are usually monitored for multiple revolutions by another device.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] This allows for geared reduction of assemblies being rotated and improved accuracy from the resolver system.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Because the power supplied to the resolvers produces no actual work, the voltages used are usually low (<24 VAC) for all resolvers.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Resolvers designed for terrestrial use tend to be driven at 50–60 Hz (utility frequency), while those for marine or aviation use tend to operate at 400 Hz (the frequency of the on-board generator driven by the engines).
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Aerospace applications utilize 2,930 Hz to 10 kHz at voltages ranging from 4 VRMS to 10 VRMS.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Many of the aerospace applications are used to determine the position of an actuator or torque motor position.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] Control systems tend to use higher frequencies (5 kHz).
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] These resolvers are used in the opposite way to transmitter resolvers (the type described above).
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The two diphased windings are energized, the ratio between the sine and the cosine representing the electrical angle.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The system turns the rotor to obtain a zero voltage in the rotor winding.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] At this position, the mechanical angle of the rotor equals the electrical angle applied to the stator.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] These types combine two diphased primary windings in one of the stacks of sheets, as with the receiver, and two diphased secondary windings in the other.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] The relation of the electrical angle delivered by the two secondary windings and the other angles is secondary electrical angle, mechanical angle, and primary electrical angle.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] These types were used, for instance, as analog trigonometric-function calculators.
[src:rotary-encoders/resolver-electrical] A related type is also the transolver, combining a two-phase winding like the resolver and a triphased winding like the synchro.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A **rotary encoder**, also called a **shaft encoder**, is an electro-mechanical device that converts the angular position or motion of a shaft or axle to analog or digital output signals.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] There are two main types of rotary encoder: absolute and incremental.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The output of an absolute encoder indicates the current shaft position, making it an angle transducer.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The output of an incremental encoder provides information about the *motion* of the shaft, which typically is processed elsewhere into information such as position, speed and distance.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] An **absolute encoder** maintains position information when power is removed from the encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The position of the encoder is available immediately on applying power.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The relationship between the encoder value and the physical position of the controlled machinery is set at assembly; the system does not need to return to a calibration point to maintain position accuracy.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] An absolute encoder has multiple code rings with various binary weightings which provide a data word representing the absolute position of the encoder within one revolution.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This type of encoder is often referred to as a parallel absolute encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A multi-turn absolute rotary encoder includes additional code wheels and toothed wheels.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A high-resolution wheel measures the fractional rotation, and lower-resolution geared code wheels record the number of whole revolutions of the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] An incremental encoder will immediately report changes in position, which is an essential capability in some applications.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] However, it does not report or keep track of absolute position.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] As a result, the mechanical system monitored by an incremental encoder may have to be homed (moved to a fixed reference point) to initialize absolute position measurements.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Digital absolute encoders produce a unique digital code for each distinct angle of the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] They come in two basic types: optical and mechanical.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A metal disc containing a set of concentric rings of openings is fixed to an insulating disc, which is rigidly fixed to the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A row of sliding contacts is fixed to a stationary object so that each contact wipes against the metal disc at a different distance from the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] As the disc rotates with the shaft, some of the contacts touch metal, while others fall in the gaps where the metal has been cut out.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The metal sheet is connected to a source of electric current, and each contact is connected to a separate electrical sensor.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The metal pattern is designed so that each possible position of the axle creates a unique binary code in which some of the contacts are connected to the current source (i.e. switched on) and others are not (i.e. switched off).
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Brush-type contacts are susceptible to wear, and consequently mechanical encoders are typically found in low-speed applications such as manual volume or tuning controls in a radio receiver.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The optical encoder's disc is made of glass or plastic with transparent and opaque areas.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A light source and photo detector array reads the optical pattern that results from the disc's position at any one time.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This code can be read by a controlling device, such as a microprocessor or microcontroller to determine the angle of the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The absolute analog type produces a unique dual analog code that can be translated into an absolute angle of the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The magnetic encoder uses a series of magnetic poles (2 or more) to represent the encoder position to a magnetic sensor (typically magneto-resistive or Hall Effect).
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The magnetic sensor reads the magnetic pole positions.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This code can be read by a controlling device, such as a microprocessor or microcontroller to determine the angle of the shaft, similar to an optical encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The absolute analog type produces a unique dual analog code that can be translated into an absolute angle of the shaft (by using a special algorithm).
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Due to the nature of recording magnetic effects, these encoders may be optimal to use in conditions where other types of encoders may fail due to dust or debris accumulation.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Magnetic encoders are also relatively insensitive to vibrations, minor misalignment, or shocks.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Built-in rotary encoders are used to indicate the angle of the motor shaft in permanent magnet brushless motors, which are commonly used on CNC machines, robots, and other industrial equipment.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In such cases, the encoder serves as a feedback device that plays a vital role in proper equipment operation.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Brushless motors require electronic commutation, which often is implemented in part by using rotor magnets as a low-resolution absolute encoder (typically six or twelve pulses per revolution).
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The resulting shaft angle information is conveyed to the servo drive to enable it to energize the proper stator winding at any moment in time.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] An asymmetrical shaped disc is rotated within the encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This disc will change the capacitance between two electrodes which can be measured and calculated back to an angular value.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A multi-turn encoder can detect and store more than one revolution.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The term absolute multi-turn encoder is generally used if the encoder will detect movements of its shaft even if the encoder is not provided with external power.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This type of encoder uses a battery for retaining the counts across power cycles.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] It uses energy conserving electrical design to detect the movements.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] These encoders use a train of gears to mechanically store the number of revolutions.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The position of the single gears is detected with one of the above-mentioned technologies.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] These encoders use the principle of energy harvesting to generate energy from the moving shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This principle, introduced in 2007, uses a Wiegand sensor to produce electricity sufficient to power the encoder and write the turns count to non-volatile memory.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] An example of a binary code, in an extremely simplified encoder with only three contacts, is shown below.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In general, where there are *n* contacts, the number of distinct positions of the shaft is 2*n*.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In this example, *n* is 3, so there are 2³ or 8 positions.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In the above example, the contacts produce a standard binary count as the disc rotates.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] However, this has the drawback that if the disc stops between two adjacent sectors, or the contacts are not perfectly aligned, it can be impossible to determine the angle of the shaft.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] To illustrate this problem, consider what happens when the shaft angle changes from 179.9° to 180.1° (from sector 3 to sector 4).
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] At some instant, according to the above table, the contact pattern changes from off-on-on to on-off-off.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] However, this is not what happens in reality.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In a practical device, the contacts are never perfectly aligned, so each switches at a different moment.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Now look at the sectors corresponding to these codes in the table.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] So, from the sequence of codes produced, the shaft appears to have jumped from sector 3 to sector 7, then gone backwards to sector 6, then backwards again to sector 4, which is where we expected to find it.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In many situations, this behaviour is undesirable and could cause the system to fail.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] For example, if the encoder were used in a robot arm, the controller would think that the arm was in the wrong position, and try to correct the error by turning it through 180°, perhaps causing damage to the arm.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] To avoid the above problem, Gray coding is used.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This is a system of binary counting in which any two adjacent codes differ by only one bit position.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] For the three-contact example given above, the Gray-coded version would be as follows.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In this example, the transition from sector 3 to sector 4, like all other transitions, involves only one of the contacts changing its state from on to off or vice versa.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This means that the sequence of incorrect codes shown in the previous illustration cannot happen.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] If the designer moves a contact to a different angular position (but at the same distance from the center shaft), then the corresponding "ring pattern" needs to be rotated the same angle to give the same output.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Since both rings are then identical, the inner ring can be omitted, and the sensor for that ring moved to the remaining, identical ring (but offset at that angle from the other sensor on that ring).
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Those two sensors on a single ring make a quadrature encoder with a single ring.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] It is possible to arrange several sensors around a single track (ring) so that consecutive positions differ at only a single sensor; the result is the single-track Gray code encoder.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The rotary incremental encoder is the most widely used of all rotary encoders due to its ability to provide real-time position information.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The measurement resolution of an incremental encoder is not limited in any way by its two internal, incremental movement sensors; one can find in the market incremental encoders with up to 10,000 counts per revolution, or more.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Rotary incremental encoders report position changes without being prompted to do so, and they convey this information at data rates which are orders of magnitude faster than those of most types of absolute shaft encoders.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Because of this, incremental encoders are commonly used in applications that require precise measurement of position and velocity.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A rotary incremental encoder may use mechanical, optical or magnetic sensors to detect rotational position changes.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The mechanical type is commonly employed as a manually operated "digital potentiometer" control on electronic equipment.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] For example, modern home and car stereos typically use mechanical rotary encoders as volume controls.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Encoders with mechanical sensors require switch debouncing and consequently are limited in the rotational speeds they can handle.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The optical type is used when higher speeds are encountered or a higher degree of precision is required.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A rotary incremental encoder has two output signals, A and B, which issue a periodic digital waveform in quadrature when the encoder shaft rotates.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This is similar to sine encoders, which output sinusoidal waveforms in quadrature (i.e., sine and cosine), thus combining the characteristics of an encoder and a resolver.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] The waveform frequency indicates the speed of shaft rotation and the number of pulses indicates the distance moved, whereas the A-B phase relationship indicates the direction of rotation.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Some rotary incremental encoders have an additional "index" output (typically labeled Z), which emits a pulse when the shaft passes through a particular angle.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Once every rotation, the Z signal is asserted, typically always at the same angle, until the next AB state change.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] This is commonly used in radar systems and other applications that require a registration signal when the encoder shaft is located at a particular reference angle.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Unlike absolute encoders, an incremental encoder does not keep track of, nor do its outputs indicate the absolute position of the mechanical system to which it is attached.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Consequently, to determine the absolute position at any particular moment, it is necessary to "track" the absolute position with an incremental encoder interface which typically includes a bidirectional electronic counter.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Inexpensive incremental encoders are used in mechanical computer mice.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Typically, two encoders are used: one to sense left-right motion and another to sense forward-backward motion.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] A Rotary (Angle) Pulse Encoder has a SPDT switch for each direction, with each one only operating in the direction of travel.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Each turn indent in one direction causes the SPDT switch associated with that direction only to toggle.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] Rotary encoders with a single output (i.e. tachometers) cannot be used to sense direction of motion but are suitable for measuring speed and for measuring position when the direction of travel is constant.
[src:rotary-encoders/rotary-encoder] In certain applications they may be used to measure distance of motion (e.g. feet of movement).
